title: Ode To Camp
author: gabrielle
text: this heaven-on-earth comforts us in the good or bad,  itâ’s a place that will always make you feel very glad.  there are lots of fun games and activities,  you will always feel relaxed and at ease.   itâ’s exciting to play in the swimming pool,  the glistening water is like a jewel.  we have cooking,  dance,  and all kinds of sports,  itâ’s better than many tropical resorts.   we go to lots of amazing places,  itâ’s so much fun; we have grins on our faces.  baseball games,  ice skating,  and many more,  every camp trip is a great time galore.   competitive activities are the best,  a few times a summer we put our skills to the test.  olympics,  battle-of-the-sexes,  and color war,  theyâ’re all so great that no one cares about the score.   itâ’s so hard to say good-bye to each and every friend,  we hate it when the summers have to come to an end.  banquet and firefly are the saddest days,  bidding farewell is the most miserable phase.   this heaven-on-earth comforts us in the good or bad,  itâ’s a place that will always make you feel very glad.  the games and activities are so much fun,  creating memories until the summers are done.

title: Paradise Once Roamed
author: hailey
text: as i walk through soft grasses,  my eyes stare upon,  the most beautiful scenery that nature as ever drawn.  my eyes view surroundings,  as the sights are raw,  i gaze upon them,  with my jaw dropped out of awe.  the spatter of color,  as the sun starts to set,  the dew on the grass as it's dripping wet.  the drifting pink clouds,  the summer breeze,  the blossomed flowers,  the green trees.  the smell of roses,  the sound of life,  not a single worry,  not a sense of strife.  the sound of rushing water from a nearby creek the feeling of health.  not a feeling of weak.  the sight of heaven,  the sight of relief,  such a shame that this moment has to be brief.  the touch of the sun,  against my skin,  i feel my face being covered with a grin.  i pluck a dandelion out of the ground,  i run through the meadow as i skip and bound.  i blow the seeds away,  and watch them fly,  i witness them soaring into the sky.  the tall oak trees release their seed,  the tiny propellers fly,  who knows where they lead.  the sky turns dark,  i start heading home,  but i always will remember,  the paradise i once roam

title: Grandma why did you have to go
author: jack
text: grandma,  why did you have to go? youâ’re probably the best person anyone will ever know.  from your childhood you were always great,   always trying to love,  and never to hate.  and as you got older you stayed the same,   when fights of hatred broke out,  you were never to blame! i donâ’t see how anyone would not want to be your friend,  how could you possibly come to an end? when you got married,  and had your kids,  you were the best parent ever,  and did one of them ever regret you as their mom,  never! all over town you were the best mom to know,   you were caring,  loving,  giving,  and even could sew.  you were always there through the good times and bad,  even when everyone was terribly sad.  and you were still loyal and loving,  as your kids grew older,   but yet as a mom and a person you just got bolder.   i really donâ’t know what anyone would do without you,  how would they learn to read,  and tie their shoe? but how could you possibly go away,  i,  for one thought you were here to stay.  then your kids got even older,  went to college,  and got married,  when by you,  already so far that theyâ’d been carried.  and eventually they had kids just like you,  you now had grandchildren,  and you became even older too.  i was one of those grandchildren,  some were girls,  others boys,  and a few already young men.  you were the best grandma a kid could dream about,   you were one of the few people i would never doubt.  and still i wonder,  how you could ever fall into that deep and final slumber.  you were one of the very best and loving people,  and not a week would go by when not at least once you had visited the church steeple.  youâ’d never let a grandchild down,  instead youâ’d make them smile,  never frown.  but you got even more grandchildren,  and for each one a spoon,  and still you were happy,  and gave off a wonderful radiance just like the moon.  yet still i just canâ’t figure out,   how you arenâ’t up and about.  as we grew older you taught us well,  and if we sinned to always tell.  she always wanted us to act christian,  and above all,  never lie,  cheat,  or start a brawl.  but then one day she became very ill,   and every day she had to take at least one pill.  the first time she got through just by a hair,  and we all got to stop holding our breath and get some fresh air.  but the second time that she got hit,  the doctors doubted even more that she would make it.  i at least thought she was here to stay,  but to everyoneâ’s horror she passed away.  grandma was the best person we could even dream about,  and with her love and care there was never a drought.  i know weâ’ll think about her every day,  and forever love her in every possible way!  thank you for what you did for the world and everyone in it grandma dody.  and always let us remember your love.

title: Memories

title: My CatÂ’s Mind
author: jared
text: my cat sits in her window with a blank stare,  the stare that makes me ponder.   what could my cat be thinking? i cannot begin to wonder what it is she is thinking.  all i can do is ponder what a cat of her caliber would think? like a dripping sink,   annoying it is how my cat does think.  maybe she thinks of the animals that run free,  outside.  if i could read her mind  i would probably find what makes her tick.  this could be a cat trick to get attention.  my racing mind does wonder.   my catâ’s mind is set on something-- something other than what i wonder.  as i tinker,  there in my chair my endless torment does not stop.  until i know what she does,  i will not stop my wonder,  nor my endless ponder.

title: Silent Mourning
author: jasmine
text: somewhere people are singing.  somewhere there's happiness,  but in the old small town,  there's not a bit of bliss.  this small town is saddened,  and all they do is sigh,  as they wait the weeks and months to pass them by.  no one's been joyful since that faithful day,  and now here's the tale they say.  once there was a family,  that sang through the town.  they sang with perfect harmony,  that the moutains would bow down.  then the family left,  and the town was full of despair,  because that cheerful family was no longer there,  and that's why no one sings in that  town,  and that's why every kid always wears a frown.  and that's my tale of that mournful little town,  who is wasting away,  because that family isn't around.                  the end

text: the morning coffee was still cooling when our grandest illusion was shattered what do you think? within minutes,  one of new yorkâ’s magnificent symbols was a smoldering mess the nationâ’s image of invincibility was a lie what do you think? as the world trade center crumbled the streets filled with screams scenes of horror choking smoke killed come out of the sun and plunged into the darkness of lower manhattan this is what happened we canâ’t change it but we can move on.
